LeetCode Problem 162: Find Peak Element

Difficulty: Medium

ğŸ§  Problem Statement:
A peak element is an element that is strictly greater than its neighbors.
You are given an array nums.
Return the index of any peak.
Assume nums[-1] = nums[n] = -âˆ, so edges can also be peaks.
Must solve in O(log n) time.

Example 1:
Input:nums = [1,2,1,3,5,6,4]
Output:5

Explanation:
-Index 1 â†’ value 2 is a peak (since 2 > 1 on both sides).
-Index 5 â†’ value 6 is a peak (since 6 > 5 and 6 > 4).
Either index 1 or 5 is valid.

âœ… Approach: (Binary Search)
-We use binary search instead of linear scan because:
-If nums[mid] > nums[mid+1], then the peak lies on the left side (including mid).
-Else, if nums[mid] < nums[mid+1], the peak lies on the right side.
-Keep shrinking the search space until left == right.
-This works because there must always be a peak due to the -âˆ boundary condition.

ğŸ“ Code:
class Solution:
    def findPeakElement(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:
        left, right = 0, len(nums) - 1

        while left < right:
            mid = (left + right) // 2
            if nums[mid] > nums[mid + 1]:
                # Peak lies on the left side (including mid)
                right = mid
            else:
                # Peak lies on the right side
                left = mid + 1

        return left

ğŸ” Dry Run:

Input: nums = [1,2,1,3,5,6,4]

left=0, right=6 â†’ mid=3 â†’ nums[3]=3, nums[4]=5
â†’ 3 < 5 â†’ peak on right â†’ left=4.
left=4, right=6 â†’ mid=5 â†’ nums[5]=6, nums[6]=4
â†’ 6 > 4 â†’ peak on left â†’ right=5.
left=4, right=5 â†’ mid=4 â†’ nums[4]=5, nums[5]=6
â†’ 5 < 6 â†’ peak on right â†’ left=5.

Now left == right == 5 â†’ return 5. âœ…

ğŸ“Š Time Complexity:
-O(log n) â†’ binary search halves the array each step.

ğŸ§  Space Complexity:
-O(1) â†’ constant extra space.
